and returned in full, along with:\n- 1 PostgreSQL setup script (setup-postgres.sql)\n- 1 data.sql file (content is same across all 6 runtime folders)\n- 5 persistence.xml files (one for each Jakarta EE runtime: Liberty, Glassfish, Payara, TomEE, and Wildfly)\n\nThe application follows a layered architecture pattern with DAO (Data Access Object) and Service layers for each domain entity (Pet, PetType, Specialty, Vet, Visit, Owner), along with entity listeners for lifecycle events and framework support classes."}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f3e9f2b3-1305-43ae-9feb-99d287ff0491","uuid":"388f9a58-1af6-4b73-96d3-4c877eafb2c4"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_bdrk_017T8chE4G1Pg4AZ2hWUwSWH","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\n\nI now have a thorough understanding of the entire codebase. Let me now begin the migration. This is a Jakarta EE 10 application using JSF/PrimeFaces, JAX-RS, EJB, CDI, and JPA that needs to be migrated to Spring Boot. The key migration strategy:\n\n1. **Entities**: Keep JPA entities (jakarta.persistence annotations stay - Spring Boot 3.x uses Jakarta)\n2. **DAOs**: Replace with Spring Data JPA repositories\n3. **Services**: Convert from @Stateless EJBs to @Service with @Transactional\n4. **REST Endpoints**: Convert JAX-RS to Spring MVC @RestController\n5. **JSF Views**: Drop entirely (not needed for REST API migration)\n6. **Configuration**: Replace persistence.xml/server.xml with application.properties"}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":32504,"cache_read_input_tokens":40733,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":32504,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":674},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f3e9f2b3-1305-43ae-9feb-99d287ff0491","uuid":"d3644dfa-5b16-4356-ba5e-93a364e3be2e"}
