final static String COL_SEARCHINDEX = \"searchindex\";\n     ```\n\n4. Specialty.java:\n   - TABLE_NAME: `public final static String TABLENAME = \"specialty\";`\n   - COL_* Constants:\n     ```\n     public final static String COL_ID = \"id\";\n     public final static String COL_UUID = \"uuid\";\n     public final static String COL_NAME = \"name\";\n     public final static String COL_SEARCHINDEX = \"searchindex\";\n     ```\n\n5. Vet.java:\n   - TABLE_NAME: `public final static String TABLENAME = \"vet\";`\n   - COL_* Constants:\n     ```\n     public final static String COL_ID = \"id\";\n     public final static String COL_UUID = \"uuid\";\n     public final static String COL_FIRSTNAME = \"first_name\";\n     public final static String COL_LASTNAME = \"lastName\";\n     public final static String COL_VET_SPECIALTIES = \"vet_specialties\";\n     public final static String COL_JOIN_VET_ID = \"vet_id\";\n     public final static String COL_JOIN_SPECIALTY_ID = \"specialty_id\";\n     public final static String COL_SEARCHINDEX = \"searchindex\";\n     ```\n\n6. Visit.java:\n   - TABLE_NAME: `public final static String TABLENAME = \"owner_pet_visit\";`\n   - COL_* Constants:\n     ```\n     public final static String COL_ID = \"id\";\n     public final static String COL_UUID = \"uuid\";\n     public final static String COL_VISIT_DATE = \"visit_date\";\n     public final static String COL_DESCRIPTION = \"description\";\n     public final static String COL_PET_ID = \"owner_pet_id\";\n     public final static String COL_SEARCHINDEX = \"searchindex\";\n     ```"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f3e9f2b3-1305-43ae-9feb-99d287ff0491","uuid":"1d3419f7-141d-4238-8511-9cf6fdb0592d"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_bdrk_014w4Pub2fBRJsFeBDLtfu4k","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I understand the issue. The `@Column` annotations specify explicit column names, but Spring Boot's `SpringPhysicalNamingStrategy` transforms them further. For example, `COL_LASTNAME = \"lastName\"` would be transformed to `last_name` by the naming strategy. The simplest fix is to configure Hibernate to use the exact column names from `@Column` annotations without transformation.\n\nHowever, there's a mixed situation:\n- `COL_LASTNAME = \"lastName\"` (camelCase - would be transformed to `last_name`)\n- `COL_FIRSTNAME = \"first_name\"` (already snake_case)\n- `COL_HOUSENUMBER = \"housenumber\"` (lowercase)\n\nThe best approach is to use `PhysicalNamingStrategyStandardImpl` so that Hibernate uses the exact `@Column` name values, and then update `data.sql` to match those exact values.\n\nLet me fix the application.properties and data.sql:"}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1390,"cache_read_input_tokens":29278,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1390,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":425},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f3e9f2b3-1305-43ae-9feb-99d287ff0491","uuid":"6ff151bf-1012-4243-a2ae-814ac7abd140"}
