{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_bdrk_01YZsoaisdvPrkm3TYYyBo6H","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Good. Now I also need to check if there are other tables in data.sql that might have similar issues. Let me also check the `house_number` field - the entity has `COL_HOUSENUMBER = \"housenumber\"` and the Java field is `houseNumber`. With `SpringPhysicalNamingStrategy`, the `@Column(name = \"housenumber\")` should stay as `housenumber` since it's already lowercase with no camelCase. Similarly for `zipcode`, `phonenumber`, `searchindex`.\n\nActually wait - I need to also check if the `@Column` name for the `houseNumber` field has an issue. The constant is `\"housenumber\"` but the Java field name is `houseNumber`. Since there IS an explicit `@Column(name = \"housenumber\")`, the naming strategy will apply to `\"housenumber\"` - which stays `housenumber`. Good.\n\nBut I also need to check: does `SpringPhysicalNamingStrategy` do anything to explicit `@Column(name=...)` values? Let me think carefully. In Spring Boot:\n1. The `SpringImplicitNamingStrategy` determines the column name if no `@Column(name=...)` is given\n2. The `SpringPhysicalNamingStrategy` is ALWAYS applied to ALL column names (including explicit ones), converting camelCase to snake_case\n\nSo `@Column(name = \"lastName\")` → physical name = `last_name`. And `@Column(name = \"housenumber\")` → physical name = `housenumber` (no change, already lowercase).\n\nThe data.sql uses `housenumber` which is correct. Let me now also verify the sequence names. The entity has `sequenceName=\"owner_seq\"` etc. With the physical naming strategy, `owner_seq` stays `owner_seq`.\n\nNow let me also verify the table names won't be affected. `@Table(name = \"owner\")` → `owner` (no change). `@Table(name = \"owner_pet\")` → `owner_pet` (no change). Good.\n\nLet me also check join table names for vet_specialties. The entity has `@JoinTable(name = COL_VET_SPECIALTIES)` where `COL_VET_SPECIALTIES = \"vet_specialties\"`. That stays `vet_specialties`. Good.\n\nNow let me mark this task complete and rebuild:"}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":959,"cache_read_input_tokens":42203,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":959,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1205},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f3e9f2b3-1305-43ae-9feb-99d287ff0491","uuid":"f0b1ffb3-2ec8-4528-ab22-91d78c097b47"}
